ve.\nBut three problems get sharper as loops get better, not easier:\nThe loop changes the work, it does not delete you from it. And three problems actually get sharper as the loop gets better, not easier.\nVerification is still on you. A loop running unattended is also a loop making mistakes unattended.\nYour understanding still rots if you allow it. The faster the loop ships code you did not write, the bigger the gap between what exists and what you actually get. Thats comprehension debt and a smooth loop just makes it grow faster unless you read what the loop made.\nAnd the comfortable posture is the dangerous one. When the loop runs itself its very tempting to stop having an opinion and just take whatever it gives back. I called that cognitive surrender. Designing the loop is the cure when you do it with judgement.\nBuild the loop. But build it like someone who intends to stay the engineer, not just the person who presses go.\n[#ai](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fai&trk=public_post_reshare-text) [#softwareengineering](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fsoftwareengineering&trk=public_post_reshare-text) [#programming](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fprogramming&trk=public_post_reshare-text)\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n![]()\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fmalen-hurbuns-3aba1631_prompting-context-engineering-now-loop-engineering-activity-7472435875155476480-2V-j&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View organization page for Veraxis Research Group (VRG)]()\n\n18 followers\n\nSoftware engineering is already moving in this direction. The new discussion around “loop engineering” is not about writing better one-off prompts. It is about designing systems that discover work, assign it to agents, check it, remember state, and continue. That is an important shift. But the same shift creates a governance problem. Once loops can operate across tools, repos, tickets, APIs, and production systems, the question is no longer only whether the loop completed the task. The question is whether every action inside the loop remained authorized, within scope, supported by evidence, and allowed to become consequence. Loop engineering gives agents operational rhythm. Runtime governance gives that rhythm a boundary.\n\n![View profile for Addy Osmani]()\n\nDirector, Google Cloud AI. Best-selling Author. Speaker. AI, DX, UX. I want to see you win.\n\nLoop engineering is replacing yourself as the person who prompts the agent. You design the system that does it instead.\nMy latest free deep dive: [https://lnkd.in/gV\\_b9AsR](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgV_b9AsR&urlhash=sZJN&trk=public_post_reshare-text) ✍\nA loop can be thought of a recursive goal where you define a purpose and the AI iterates until complete. I believe this may be the future of how we work with coding agents. However, its still early and you absolutely have to be careful about token costs.\nFor two years, the way you got something out of a coding agent was simple: write a good prompt, read what came back, write the next prompt. You held the tool the whole time, one turn after another.\nThat part is changing.\nPeter Steinberger of OpenClaw put it like this: \"You shouldn't be prompting coding agents anymore. You should be designing loops that prompt your agents.\" Boris Cherny, head of Claude Code, said the same thing differently: \"I don't prompt Claude anymore. I have loops running that prompt Claude.\"\nA loop is five things:\n→ Automations - a heartbeat that runs discovery on a schedule so you're not the one going around checking\n→ Worktrees - isolated branches so parallel agents don't collide on the same files\n→ Skills - project knowledge written down once so the agent doesn't re-derive your conventions from scratch every run\n→ Plugins/connectors - MCP connections to your real tools, so the loop opens PRs and updates tickets instead of just telling you what it would do if it could\n→ Sub-agents - one agent writes, a different agent checks. The one who wrote the code is too nice grading its own homework.\nPlus one more thing that sounds too simple to matter: a memory file. Markdown, a Linear board, anything that lives outside the conversation. The agent forgets between runs. The repo doesn't.\nWhat surprised me is this isn't a bespoke scripting problem anymore. A year ago building a loop meant a pile of bash only you could maintain. Now the pieces ship inside the products. Claude Code and Codex both have all five.\nBut three problems get sharper as loops get better, not easier:\nThe loop changes the work, it does not delete you from it. And three problems actually get sharper as the loop gets better, not easier.\nVerification is still on you. A loop running unattended is also a loop making mistakes unattended.\nYour understanding still rots if you allow it. The faster the loop ships code you did not write, the bigger the gap between what exists and what you actually get. Thats comprehension debt and a smooth loop just makes it grow faster unless you read what the loop made.\nAnd the comfortable posture is the dangerous one. When the loop runs itself its very tempting to stop having an opinion and just take whatever it gives back. I called that cognitive surrender. Designing the loop is the cure when you do it with judgement.\nBuild the loop. But build it like someone who intends to stay the engineer, not just the person who presses go.\n[#ai](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fai&trk=public_post_reshare-text) [#softwareengineering](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fsoftwareengineering&trk=public_post_reshare-text) [#programming](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fprogramming&trk=public_post_reshare-text)\n\n![No alternative text description for this image]()\n\n\n\n\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fvrg-aep_software-engineering-is-already-moving-in-activity-7470104850241048577-Nvs7&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n![View profile for Travis Frisinger]()\n\nThe most useful part of Addy's loop-engineering piece isn't what gets faster.\nIt's that he's honest about what gets worse.\nHe names three problems that sharpen as the loop improves: verification stays on you, comprehension debt compounds, cognitive surrender is the trap. I've spent the last 3 months building a Dark Factory (HydraFlow) around one answer to all three: the safeguards have to be loops too. Verification, documentation, governance, none of them can depend on a human staying heroic.\nSo HydraFlow isn't one loop. It's a fleet of specialized worker loops, each owning one stage of the lifecycle, coordinated by labels as a state machine: an issue's labels are its state, and each loop picks up the work addressed to it. The loops that build are only half of them. The other half exist to keep the first half honest.\nVerification. Addy's right that a second agent helps, because the author is \"too nice grading its own homework.\" But the grader drifts lenient too. What holds is an acceptance gate independent of the work it judges, with criteria written before the work starts, that fails loudly when they aren't met: a gate the implementer can't relax, a four-layer test pyramid (unit, integration, scenario, and end-to-end), and review loops that repeat until a pass finds nothing material.\nComprehension debt. His best line is that the agent forgets but the repo doesn't. We pushed that until keeping understanding fresh is itself a loop, not a chore anyone has to remember. Caretaker loops rewrite the wiki from live pipeline events, regenerate the architecture diagrams on every change, and enforce a canonical glossary: when a term drifts from how the code actually uses it, CI fails. The shared language is a build artifact, not a hallway convention. Understanding can't rot quietly, because drift is a build break, not a vibe.\nCognitive surrender. The cure isn't \"pay more attention.\" It's governance written into the loop, explicit rules for when an agent acts versus escalates to a human, plus legibility: a system forced to keep explaining itself in language it can't let go stale is one you can step back into and actually understand. You can't surrender to a system that refuses to stay opaque.\nSo the durable asset isn't the model or the prompt. It isn't even the loop. It's encoded, continuously-verified process knowledge. A loop whose process lives only in prompts is tribal knowledge with extra steps. The boring written parts are what survive the next model swap.\nBuild the loop. Then encode your judgment into it, so it pulls you up a level of abstraction instead of out of the work.\n➜ I'm going deep on exactly this at GOTO Accelerate Chicago on June 24: \"Self-Building Software: Lessons from the HydraFlow Experiment.\" If you'll be there, come find me.\n[https://lnkd.in/gznBJBU9](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FgznBJBU9&urlhash=qE6e&trk=public_post-text)\n\n![View profile for Addy Osmani]()\n\nDirector, Google Cloud AI. Best-selling Author. Speaker. AI, DX, UX. I want to see you win.\n\nLoop engineering is replacing yourself as the person who prompts the agent. You design the system that does it instead.\nMy latest free deep dive: [https://lnkd.in/gV\\_b9AsR](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%